     <text:p text:style-name="P78"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#c0_Lettres_a_un_gentilhomme_russe_sur_l_inquisition_espagnole.xhtml#cite_ref-65" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="Definition"><text:span text:style-name="T6">↑</text:span></text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">The whole tyranny of the Inquisition ; though without its order, was introduced in the kingdom</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6"> (Hume’s history of England. James the 1617 [sic], ch. LVII, in-4o, pag. 109.) Hume sans </text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="T6">s’en apercevoir, s’exprime ici d’une manière assez inexacte. Un tribunal qui marche environné de lois et de formes, appuyé sur la </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">miséricorde</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6"> autant que sur la </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">justice,</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6"> ne peut être que </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">sévère.</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6"> Celui qui condamne sans formalités est purement et simplement </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">assassin,</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6"> et, comme tel, exécrable.</text:span></text:p>
